    },
    {
      "id": "1a7ce702d065017015811d66bc403481f99df97d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2018-04-02 22:31:14.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis moves the code backward from patch http://review.whamcloud.com/11993 \"LU-5443 libcfs: replace direct HZ access with kernel APIs\".  Rather than proliferating the use of HZ/jiffies around the code, wouldn't it be better to move all of the timers over to msec/nsec?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "601fb266d168864164d0156cb478c07d350ea5e5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2018-04-03 14:20:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJames, in the commit message you wrote \"Also using msecs_to_jiffies() no longer works to get around the variable jiffiess issue. With all uses of HZ being to the local node it is safe to remove the wrapper.\"\n\nCould you explain why it no longer works?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "6f1818b440b666a76879559ecad4185fd99ac259",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 377,
        "name": "wc-checkpatch",
        "username": "hpdd-checkpatch",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2018-04-09 21:09:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nThis change cannot be cherry-picked to master.\nPlease rebase the change locally and upload the rebased commit for review.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c5b7f59509502841a193070c62089d97ccb206fd",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-04-09 21:29:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe reason it doesn't work anymore is that for newer kernels msecs_to_jiffies() is now an inline function in jiffies.h. This was done to deal with odd HZ values that don't divide evenly into milliseconds.  The real function is __msecs_to_jiffies but I see comments about depending on HZ not being greater than 1000. I don't trust that will be the case. I think the best approach is to move to nsecs_to_jiffies().",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "fc4bd341524a966e6d9fc5016afa119227960963",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-05-15 14:33:21.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI started to update this patch to unroll cfs_time_seconds() but I like to ask is it needed? Should we live with cfs_time_seconds() since its a out of tree problem.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "accd05c7a65788c94fc7048507f6d0310651b616",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2018-07-13 14:47:37.000000000",
      "message": "Abandoned\n\nSince this is  an out of tree problem we can keep this last wrapper. Thankfully its a rare problem now.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    }
